# Day 1/30: Why did Transformers replace RNNs and LSTMs?

Starting something new — a 30-day series where I go back to basics on Transformers, and by the end, try to build a tiny LLM from scratch. Mostly so I understand it deeply enough to explain it simply. Let's start at the beginning.

For a long time, RNNs and LSTMs were the default choice for anything sequential — text, speech, time series. They read input one token at a time, carrying a "memory" forward as they went.

Sounds reasonable. But it had real problems.

First, training was painfully sequential. Each step depended on the one before it, so you couldn't really parallelize things. Long sequences meant long training times.

Second, memory faded fast. By the time an LSTM got to word 50 in a sentence, word 1 was basically a distant memory. Long-range context just didn't stick.

Third, scaling didn't help much. Throwing more data or compute at these models gave diminishing returns.

Then in 2017, the "Attention Is All You Need" paper flipped the approach. Instead of reading word by word, why not let the model look at the *entire* sequence at once, and figure out which words matter most to each other — no matter how far apart they are?

That one idea — attention — is the reason GPT, BERT, Claude, and basically every modern LLM work the way they do.

